segments.text: I want to mention something I want to make sure I covered.
Please do.
Over the, you know, the constant thing over the 30 or so years
has been teaching that one course and being a graduate advisor in the department.
So a lot of interaction with undergraduate and graduate students,
which I've enjoyed in both cases.
And I've been offered, I mean, I've been asked so many times,
how in the world do you keep teaching that same course for 30 years?
Well, that I don't know.
I don't really have an answer for that,
except it's different students every semester.
This is my last semester to do it this time,
and I've just as decided about doing it as I'd ever be.
It kind of feels funny.
You just can't imagine not continuing to do it, to tell you the truth.
But I've continued to enjoy it.
But I've always tried to, at least every couple of semesters,
do something different about the course.
Add something about putting, redoing audio tapes,
or now I've put all the objectives on the web.
Last semester I did that.
So something to keep me a little bit current.
And something also to use different visual aids.
And never to be too rigid in the lecture.
Always.
Kind of let it flow and cover things in a different order.
But in addition to that, I think in the university community,
there's so many opportunities to, I guess, be a servant or grow yourself.
And so over the years, I've advised student clubs.
Sometimes many as four at one time, but mainly I've always had at least one.
Advised core outfits.
Served as advisor to the political forum, student group,
shortly after that.
Got to meet Gerald Ford and a few other prominent people in those years.
And enjoyed the heck out of that.
Then served a couple of years on the MSC Consulate Directorate.
Had a different kind of experience.
Faculty senate in the department.
Said, you know, we need to have somebody from the department be on the faculty senate.
So I get, I mean, I didn't say anything to anybody.
I get nominated and I end up on the faculty senate.
And then.
Uh.
Hold on a second.
Hold on a second.
Hold on a second.
Hold on a second.
Hold on a second.
Hold on a second.
Hold on a second.
Hold on a second.
Hold on a second.
Hold on a second.
Hold on a second.
So, uh, Fred Smynes over in Rainside said, well, it's a shame.
We're just going to let John McNerney be the first speaker with no competition at all.
Somebody ought to run against him.
Wilford, you run against him.
Well, I did.
Well, of course, unfortunate and deservedly John, he's elected.
But John makes me the deputy.
And then of course, this greases the wheel for me to be the speaker of the next year.
But I'm keeping all my teaching duties and all my advice all at the same time.
But that was a, see that was an outlet, a different, and of course the speaker year
was a, that was a tremendous experience to interact with all of the higher administrators
and that kind of deal and it was a, it was an exciting time for the Senate trying to
get established.
Did the Senate, did the Senate come up with any recommendation that you thought
was a little goofy that you still had as their voice to support?
Well, I don't remember, the only, and this happened actually after my year as speaker
was over, the core curriculum was being developed during that year, all that year.
And I'm not particularly proud of it, but I ended up in the final analysis voting against
the final adoption of the core curriculum.
Not because I opposed the core curriculum, but because there was always in the development
of it, there had been a quote, a technological requirement.
Yeah.
And I didn't anticipate it anymore.
And this got washed out at the end and I felt so strongly about that that I ended up voting
no and I didn't feel real good about that, but I didn't have to promote that to the Senate.
I, no, I don't remember anything, I'm trying to remember, it had something to do with women's
program or something, gosh I don't know if I have any notes about this or not, but Dr.
Shaffer called me into his office and he was mad as a hornet, I mean he was off the
wall for just two or three minutes.
Then he calmed down and we had a good conversation, but I, it was, it was something about the
women's program.
I think something that Ms. Shaffer, that Dr. Shaffer was a, was a woman in charge of the
women's committee program.
Yeah.
I don't, I don't remember the particulars, but I do remember Dr. Vandiver was, he was
mightily upset when the first one in, but he calmed down, he calmed down.
What do you think?
But, but I did that and then I, I became a continuous improvement facilitator, and I've
served on a...
Let's stay, let's stay with faculty Senate just a second.
What do you think the faculty's role in decision making for this institution ought to be?
You know, I'm kind of comfortable with the, the Senate being in an advisory role.
I, I don't, I don't, I'm not one of those that quote thinks the faculty needs to make
all the decisions, because I don't, the faculty is just one component in the whole university
community and the, and the university president ultimately, yeah, an organized venue by which
the faculty can make its, to make its feelings known.
Yeah.
And I think on matters of academics, it's, I would hope, I would hope that the president,
and I think all of them have, tended to support Senate decisions, but there have been exceptions,
I guess, but.
In the department, should there be a department head or a department chairman?
For, for a department like ours with a three agency deal and, and responsibilities out
state and in state.
I think it needs to be a head.
On Wednesday, whether or not they qualified or not.
Well, I think it, I don't know, but I remember it, it worked back three or four days.
Oh, so it got earlier and earlier.
It kept getting earlier and earlier.
You had to turn in senior grades.
And it came fast.
Because seniors are just, I mean, I taught a big class that would have 25% seniors, and
I guess I did, I guess I did begin to get a little chapped about them not taking finals,
because they would put off classes like mine for the last semester, so they didn't have
to take my finals.
Of all of those services, which ones were the most satisfying to you as you look back?
Each one while I was doing it.
I wouldn't want to pick one.
I, I guess the most different, of course, was being speaker at the Faculty Senate for
a year.
Maybe that was the hideous kind of a deal.
Get your ticket, you know.
Yeah.
Get your tickets to the Texas game in Austin.
We won.
A few things like that I remember very well.
But, no, in the early days, being an advisor to a corps outfit, having come through the
corps, there were a lot of good experiences associated with that.
How do you feel about the corps as you look back on it now?
What do you feel about the corps today?
Much more military than it was then.
Is it better or worse?
Plus?
Minus?
I haven't had real close contact in recent years, enough to see much on the inside.
I think it's been about, yeah, much, many more people, I guess you could say, many more
people in the corps who really have a, have a kind of a pro-military posture.
See, when I came through the corps, many of us were there because we had to be there.
It was either be in the corps or be in Korea.
The corps was preferable.
So, you had a, you had a major, major influence in the corps of people who were, yeah, you
know, we could, we could kind of tolerate the bull and that kind of stuff and enjoy
some of it, but we never had any dream about being a military somebody.
I feel like there's been more, I think a lot of that's been, maybe gotten rid of in
recent years, but I feel like there's been a lot more of what I would just call really
cheap stuff.
During those, all those years, describe a typical week for you during the academic
year.
What, you started at Monday and did what and how long and so forth.
Take a thorough week.
How many nights were you busy and so forth?
Well, with all of the kind of extracurricular activities and things I've had, there were
probably, there were probably not very many nights when I didn't have a meeting or do
something at home related to the job.
I've normally, I've been a bicycle rider for a long time.
I've normally, and I like to get here on the bicycle before the traffic gets too bad, and
I've normally not gone home until it, it's not too bad again.
So, I've been a bicycle rider for a long time.
I've typically been at work from 7.30, 7.45 in the morning until 5.30 or 6 in the afternoon
and usually bring lunch.
We have a bridge playing group here, lunch, but during the school year, most of the time
I've had an 8 o'clock class on Monday, Wednesday, Friday.
So, you have to get here early to be ready to go for that, and I've had 11.30 for many
years now.
So, even for the bridge playing group, that cuts you lunch hours.
Now, what was this second class?
The same class.
Oh, same.
Two sections.
Two sections.
Two sections.
Okay.
Okay.
And what did you tell your students that your office hours were for them to come by?
You never had an office hour.
Door was open.
I always told them the door was open.
Call me.
Now it's email.
You're welcome to come in any time you can catch me.
That's what, that's what I always said.
But I've never, I've never set the bridge at office hours.
How would you compare the quality of the students now with the students when you first got here?
That's a hard read.
I suspect, I suspect the overall quality in terms of academic capability is better.
In terms of maturity, in the sense of the student knowing who they are and what they're
about, it's not as good now as it was then.
Class attendance generally is much poorer than it was in those days.
Students can't take nearly as heavy a load as I do it.
They have, I don't know how many of them spend their time, but I mean, I can visualize
some of the options when you see them unload all the things they have.
I mean, there's TV.
There's the internet.
There's the computer.
There's music.
There's, all of them have cars.
They're mobile.
They leave here on weekends.
So, it's, I just think there's a, there are a lot of competing things for students' attention.
I, I don't see as much interest in learning, as a general rule.
I just don't see as much interest in learning.
And your students didn't get a degree, but I don't see much interest in learning.
And I think that's what we need to do.
I mean, I think we need to do some of the things that we were doing in the early 20s
and early 30s and the early 30s and the early 30s.
And I don't see that as much interest in learning.
I think we have to do something about that.
So, do you think that you're getting a little bit more experience in the course that you've
been doing all these years?
Do you think you're, how does your grading system now in other words, what does it take
to make an A now compared to then?
I'd like to tell you it hasn't changed much, but not nearly as many make A's now as it
did then.
Is that right?
No sir.
What about flunking?
Well, many more today.
Many more?
Many more.
What about flunking?
Many more today.
Many more.
Many more.
Yeah, 1 to 3 percent in the early days.
It runs in the 7, 6 to 10 now.
I always thought I had to have at least 15 percent A's in class.
I mean, I felt bad if I didn't have at least 15 percent A's.
And lots of semesters I'd have over 50 percent A's and B's.
But not now.
About 35 percent A's and B's now most of the time.
It varies from semester to semester.
Last summer, not this past summer, but something before, I had a real good class.
But this past summer, terrible.
Now, this fall, looks like, I mean, I had 142 out of 162 in class Monday.
Well, that's not bad.
What about women enrollment in the class now compared to years ago?
Well, I've had some summer classes with more women than men.
This semester, seems that my percentage of women is quite a bit lower than it's been
some time.
And I'm assuming far more urban kids now.
Oh, yeah.
For sure.
Many internationals in the undergraduate course?
Not many.
Probably 5 percent less.
I bet there are a lot more from broken homes than there would have been 20 years ago.
I think that's the big change.
I think kids are about as honest as they've ever been.
I think the abilities they have.
The abilities there.
I think the maturity factor in terms of them feeling good about themselves.
Having a well-developed ethos, code to live by.
I just think many of them are not there.
Do you have much indication of scholastic dishonesty now?
No, I wouldn't say.
That's what I say.
I think they're about as honest as they've ever been.
I don't see, I've had a little of that all along, but I don't think they're any less
honest.
I think, I've always said students tend to live up or down to your expectations in that
arena.
You have high expectations in terms of honesty.
I think you generally get it.
How many students do you reckon you taught in that class?
I have a record downstairs.
I don't think I made 18,000, but I'm close.
Between 17,500 and 18,000.
All right, now I'm getting near the end.
Among your departmental colleagues, to whom do you feel the greatest appreciation?
I'm not going to ask you the negative.
Which colleagues are you more grateful to?
Well, probably Larry Wilding in terms of his ability to do things.
Larry Wilding in terms of what a colleague has meant to me personally in my own professional
life.
I think a lot of people in the department would probably say that.
Larry's made us all better.
He's certainly been a strong plus for me in some of the things I've been able to experience
and do.
Hank Mills was somebody I always have a lot of respect for.
He was a very different guy.
We had a master's degree.
Oh, he's a Texas country boy.
But I guess in early years, I had about as close association with him as anybody.
Some pretty good country wisdom there that he could impart.
He could read students.
He could read students.
You're inferring he was a buddy?
Yeah, kind of.
Yeah.
Who's been your closest buddies, friends in the department or elsewhere?
You know, I don't think I could say that I've been, I don't think I've singled on anybody
like that.
We have a departmental bridge group that gets together once a month, and so I guess Larry
and Gladys.
Larry and Gladys are probably, by virtue of church and department and everything, have
probably been closer to this.
They were quite close to the Runge's during their years here.
Marcia was always close to Darce Darby.
And Cedric Van Buechman lives down the street, but I was never, you know, always like to
interact with Ron and Hans, but never, I've never, I guess you'd have to say Larry, and
yet we don't spend a lot of time together.
All right.
Looking up in the hierarchy, to whom do you think, because of what they have meant to
the institution, do you feel the greatest gratitude at the college and at the institutional
level?
Who's been, who did the most to make A&M better, you think, at the college, or at the
leadership?
Well, of course, I don't have that whole perception.
Oh.
University, I'd have to say Earl Rutter.
Okay.
And it doesn't have to be just one.
He was the man in the spot at the time.
I mean, he obviously, his service here preceded me, but I think he probably considered where
A&M was when it came, or where it was going when he left.
He probably had the most profound influence on anybody that I could think of.
Anybody?
In the college?
I'm guessing that Patterson probably did as much to wake it up to what it could possibly
be.
And, you know, I don't know.
I don't know.
I don't know.
I don't know.
I don't know.
I don't know.
I don't know.
I don't know.
I don't know.
I don't know.
I don't know.
I don't know.
I don't know.
I don't know.
But I'm guessing that Patterson probably did as much to wake it up to what it could
possibly be, and that's more hearsay than any knowledge.
I've never done any.
Very big study on that.
Probably Harry Conkle.
He had strengths and weaknesses, but I think I'd have to say Harry.
Okay.
Now.
The department has to be Bloodworth, without a shadow of a doubt.
That's make believe that you've been required.
recruited now as the consultant to advise the department and the college
and the institution of what it should do in the future?
What would you advise this
department to do in the future?
I'm going to go at it the backward way a little bit.
Okay.
Institution.
I hope we don't lose sight of what it is that I think makes A&M unique in terms of can-do attitude,
friendliness, openness, that kind of thing.
And I think some of those things that contribute most to making it,
well, I've always said in my classes, you know, I've been to Wisconsin, I've been to Cornell, I've been here,
I'm not about to tell you that Texas A&M is the best institution I've ever been associated with,
but I am going to tell you it's unique.
And I really believe it's unique.
And particularly what I consider to be the best institution in the world.
I think there are positive parts of that uniqueness I hope we don't lose.
And I don't think those points are going to help us be top ten.
I mean, I think if you get all wrapped up in being top ten, we can lose some things that may not contribute to just being top ten,
but make us unique in a desirable way.
So I hope as an institution we don't lose sight of that.
In the department,
there are obviously,
there needs to be an ability to bring all areas along in it.
Well, we're going to have to identify, probably to an extent we haven't done,
we're going to have to identify the areas where we want to be top flight
and where we just want to be, meet our quote, academic responsibilities.
I don't think we can be, I don't think we can be everything to everybody.
And I think, I think,
I think at the college level,
I think Ed Heiler has a,
you know, that's one of the things I kind of fault him on.
I think he,
I think he's not gotten beyond us thinking we'd be everything to everybody.
So we've not made some hard decisions there that we probably could make.
And we probably haven't made some hard ones in the department that we need to make.
The balance that right now,
in terms of grant dollars,
the biotech, genetics, molecular biology,
they're swinging the big stick.
I think there's a threat to the whole land grant system
stemming out of this with the increased emphasis on patenting genes,
on getting royalties that goes back into plant breeders and geneticists' pockets.
That an increasing percentage of the support to do the research is coming from
soft money, soft money sources.
There's not, there,
there tends to be not nearly in new faculty
the sense of servanthood
that I think
befits people in colleges of agriculture and land grant institutions.
We're losing some of that.
And it's causing,
and maybe that's the biggest challenge I see in the department,
is to maintain that,
that spirit of serving the taxpayers who make it possible for you to be here
and not have such a high emphasis on feathering your own nest.
It tends to become more materialistic as a faculty.
I don't like that.
Are there some specialties within this department's scope
that you think ought to get emphasis?
You said it can't be all things to all people.
Well, for the major,
for the major commodities in the state,
grain, sorghum,
corn, cotton,
small grains, we need to maintain a continuity of expertise from the very base level to the top.
Because in many cases,
the market for the products is not sufficiently large that it's going to attract
the large, seed companies.
And they're getting bigger all the time.
So they only want to do things that are,
where there's a big market for a product.
So we have to,
we have to meet the niche for those commodities.
We have to maintain expertise in,
in soil science as it relates to land use in the broadest sense,
from waste disposal,
to, to conservation,
to, to,
to, to,
to, to,
to, to,
to, to,
to, to,
to, to,
to, to,
to, to,
to, to,
to, to,
to, to preservation,
to, to,
agricultural production to sustainability.
More and more,
were going to see the emphasis to be more and less short term.
There's going to be more environmental oriented,
more urban concern oriented than it is has been the traditional field crop agriculture.
But here's some boxing copying it,
but I think we be terribly or at least if we get our.
Better expertise.
In the web.
Got, got,
got.
in the broad range of soil science, Paul.
But we can't be really expert in all those areas,
and I'd say we'd probably sacrifice some of what would have been a traditional basic science,
like soil physics or have to have people that are functioning more at the interface
maybe between, let's say, soils and environmental concerns, soils ecology,
environment, a little bit more emphasis on integrating that,
and hopefully a lot more cooperation between departments.
You know, the department wall is a terrible barrier.
Now we have the faculties that are across departments.
I don't know.
There's no easy answer to that kind of thing.
If we could smooth out the barriers that prevent faculty from interacting across departmental walls
and make sure that we have a better environment,
I don't think we'd be able to do that.
And faculty walls and college walls seem to be functioning better between universities
than they can between right here on our own campus in some instances.
You know, that's a big deal with Douglas.
He's got us interacting more, but one can do it and do it in two different things.
What were your proudest moments in all these years as a faculty member here?
I guess maybe getting a note from a...
student that's in whose life the note seems to say that you've had a very positive impact on them.
Because I know how many people think they're going to have a note like that and never do.
And how many times I've thought about doing something like that and didn't do it.
So when I...
I think that would be my proudest moment,
is to get those favorable comments from...
and they're not a whole lot of them, but when you do get them.
Question.
Summarize what you have in your heart about what it's meant to you to be a faculty member here.
Well, I feel just extremely fortunate and blessed.
I mean, I couldn't have done what I love to do and got paid for it.
Family's had a good living.
It's been...
I've felt that I've had wonderful support,
a lot of opportunities,
turned around with literally thousands, thousands of students at both graduate and undergraduate levels.
